<assessment id="u3_m1_rules2_tutor3">
   <title>Tutor</title>
   <page>
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>The probability of "not L" is:</p>
      </body>
      <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
         <choice value="Res1">0.86</choice>
         <choice value="Res2">0.74</choice>
         <choice value="Res3">1.6</choice>
         <choice value="Res4">0.65</choice>
      </multiple_choice>
      <part>
         <response match="Res1" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Note that .86 is
                  P(<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T115653-0500" content=" "?>not
                  I), and you are asked to find P(not L). </feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res2" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Note that .74 is
                  P(<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T115656-0500" content=" "?>not
                  H), and you are asked to find P(not L). </feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res3" score="0">
            <feedback>This answer must be
                  wrong<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T115714-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                  since the probability of any event takes values only between 0 and 1. Therefore,
                  whatever method you used to get to this answer is incorrect, and you should avoid
                  using it again. You are asked to find P(not L). Note that P(L) is given in the
                  problem description, so all you need to do is to apply the complement
                  rule.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res4" score="10">
            <feedback>Correct.  Indeed, using the complement rule, P(not L) = 1 - P(L) = 1 - 0.35 =
               0.65.</feedback>
         </response>
      </part>
   </question></page>
